CSS Selector (Cascading Style Sheet):
    - Another way of locating elements on the webpage
    - Syntax: tagName[attribute = 'attribute value']
            ex: input[value = 'LOGIN']
Shortcuts for CSS:
    - className --> .
        syntax: TagName.classNameValue
            ex: input.button
    - ID --> #
        syntax: tagName#idValue
            ex: input#txtPassword
Contains() method in CSS:
    - * represents contains method
        syntax: tagName[attribute *= 'partial attribute value']
            ex: input[placeholder *= 'phone']
Starts-With method in CSS:
    - ^ represents starts-with method
        syntax: tagName[attribute ^= 'starting attribute value']
            ex: input[aria-label ^= 'Pass']
Ends-With method in CSS:
    - $ represents ends-with method
        syntax: tagName[attribute $= 'ending attribute value']
            ex: a[href $= 'login']

Xpath vs CSS:
    - CSS cannot locate elements via text (Xpath can)
    - Xpath cannot locate elements via ends-with (CSS can)
    - CSS has shortcuts
    - CSS is faster than Xpath in locating elements
    - CSS has more simple syntax than Xpath

WebElement Commands:
    - consists of several methods where we can perform an action and get the element state on the webpage
      - isEnabled() --> boolean
      - isDisplayed() --> boolean
      - isSelected() --> boolean
      - clear() --> void
      - getText() --> String
      - getAttribute() --> String
      - submit() --> void